1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
 Good morning, church.

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:03,000
 Good morning.

3
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:06,000
 Good morning. My name is Justin. I'm one of the pastors here.

4
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
 I've seen you guys, but if this is your first time here, everyone watching online,

5
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:14,000
 I just want to say hi. My name is Justin.

6
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
 And we just want to say, those of you who have left Hong Kong recently,

7
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:21,000
 friends all around the world watching, we miss you here.

8
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:26,000
 At the same time, I want to welcome friends returning to spend the holidays here.

9
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:29,000
 You know who you are. I just want to do a special shout-out.

10
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 Now, in this Advent series, we've been looking at different characters from the Christmas story,

11
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:40,000
 entering their narratives with a bit of biblical imagination.

12
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 And the central question that we are asking ourselves in this season of Advent

13
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:51,000
 is what kind of false kings are currently reigning in our hearts?

14
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:53,000
 Because we need to dethrone them.

15
00:00:53,000 --> 00:01:00,000
 We need to recognize what they are so that we could make more room for our true king.

16
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 Actually, speaking of room, if you have a seat beside you,

17
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:12,000
 could you--can I ask you kindly to move in so that more people who are standing can have a seat?

18
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
 And I really appreciate that. Thank you.

19
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:18,000
 So let me recap where we are right now.

20
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:23,000
 Last week, Pastor Andrew spoke about the need to dethrone Herod,

21
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:32,000
 who represents our incessant need to control things and to be the center of attention.

22
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:36,000
 And last week, Pastor Allison, through the story of Zechariah,

23
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:40,000
 taught us that doubt can lead us astray, but at the same time,

24
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:44,000
 doubt is healthy and it is necessary for us.

25
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:50,000
 Today, we explore in more detail one of the more celebrated and yet highly disputed aspects

26
00:01:50,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 of the traditional Christmas story, where there was no room for Mary and Joseph

27
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,000
 to have baby Jesus in Bethlehem.

28
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:06,000
 And this resulted in Jesus being born and needing to be born in less than ideal circumstances,

29
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:12,000
 in a dark, damp stable. And some would even argue that it's a cave.

30
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:16,000
 Now, many scholars have discussed, and I'm going to summarize for us,

31
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:21,000
 that the actual issue that Bethlehem had was not a housing crisis,

32
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:30,000
 but in fact, it was their unwillingness to open up their homes to a pregnant and unmarried woman.

33
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
 Through scriptures, we can see that Mary, of course, accepted God's will for her,

34
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:39,000
 and she meditated upon her heart the message of Gabriel

35
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:43,000
 and what God is about to do throughout humanity.

36
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:47,000
 But scriptures also say that Mary was troubled.

37
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 Not just troubled, but she was deeply disturbed.

38
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:55,000
 She was distressed, she was unnerved, she was anxious,

39
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:59,000
 because she was carrying the Son of God.

40
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:03,000
 And also, she was disturbed because pregnancy, outside of marriage,

41
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 in first century Jewish society, was regarded as an absolute horror.

42
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:17,000
 As a result of her obedience to God, Mary would have become an outcast of society.

43
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 Her reputation would have been deeply tarnished,

44
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:27,000
 she would have carried personal disgrace and exclusion, literal exclusion from her community.

45
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:33,000
 And I want to add that this shame implicates not just Mary, but Joseph and their wider families,

46
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
 and everyone associated with Mary and Joseph.

47
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 So you can imagine how devastating emotionally and relationally this is on everyone,

48
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:45,000
 not just Mary and Joseph.

49
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:49,000
 What becomes more shocking, as if this is not enough,

50
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:54,000
 Mary and Joseph realized upon arrival, having traveled near and far,

51
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:59,000
 while pregnant, through dangerous roads, just to get to Bethlehem.

52
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:04,000
 What was shocking to them is that most of Bethlehem were Joseph's relatives

53
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:09,000
 who did not open up their house and their homes and their hearts to them.

54
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:14,000
 Because Bethlehem, in short, did not want to be associated with a woman

55
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 who was believed to be a sinner.

56
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:23,000
 And next, in the Christmas story, it says that Mary is in birth pangs,

57
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:27,000
 and of course, baby Jesus is born.

58
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:32,000
 Church, I want to say that the central characters in today's message

59
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:37,000
 is actually not Joseph and Mary, but rather the people of Bethlehem.

60
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
 Because what lies beneath or behind this famous Christmas story

61
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:44,000
 is something that all of us can relate to.

62
00:04:44,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 That is something universal and common to all of us in our everyday life.

63
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:54,000
 So today, I'm going to ask you, as I share, as I preach,

64
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 I'm going to ask you, invite you, to use your imagination with me,

65
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:03,000
 to exercise some biblical imagination.

66
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:09,000
 Because I wonder, beyond the shame and stigma Mary's pregnancy brought,

67
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,000
 what other reasons do you think caused the entire town of Bethlehem,

68
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 Joseph's own relatives, to shun them completely?

69
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:22,000
 To begin, maybe I just want you to remember a recent time

70
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 where you were offended because the people that you sought understanding,

71
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:32,000
 that you sought friendship and a moment of companion,

72
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:38,000
 you sought refuge, mutually did not extend themselves to you.

73
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:44,000
 I just want you to remember, if you can, a recent time and how you felt.

74
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:48,000
 Last year, I had a solo trip to Fukuoka.

75
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 I haven't traveled by myself in 12 years, so it was a joy.

76
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 I had a week there just to reflect at the end of the year.

77
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:01,000
 Anyways, one of the things I was looking forward to

78
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 was trying out this highly recommended Japanese-Italian carbonara fusion restaurant.

79
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 I'm not a foodie myself, but when I'm traveling, you just do what locals do.

80
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:14,000
 One night, I got lost. One day, I got lost.

81
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:19,000
 I decided not to use Google Maps, and I wandered into this really chic area.

82
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 And lo and behold, guess what?

83
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:24,000
 This was the restaurant that my friend highly recommended me to try out.

84
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 Now, I know you're going to judge me because I didn't make a booking.

85
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:31,000
 Once again, I got lost, and I just said, "Hey, I'm on vacation. I'm going to take it easy."

86
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:35,000
 So anyways, I walked in, and I politely asked, "Is there a table of one?"

87
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:38,000
 This was at 6 p.m. There were only three parties here,

88
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:43,000
 and of course, I saw a lot of empty seats, especially a bar with single seats.

89
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 And in their polite Japanese mannerisms, they said, "Sorry, sir. We are fully booked."

90
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:54,000
 And I thought, "Okay. Clearly, I don't understand that."

91
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:59,000
 So I took out my Google Translate, and I said, "Hey, I just want to try one of your carbonaras,

92
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 and I'll be out within half an hour. Can I please sit here?"

93
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 And in their uttermost polite Japanese mannerisms, once again,

94
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:12,000
 they smiled and nodded and said, "Sorry, sir. We do not have any room."

95
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 Now, once again, I don't normally get upset about this stuff, but I was disappointed.

96
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 I was sad. I did feel a little bit rejected because all I really wanted to know was,

97
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:31,000
 "Why couldn't I have a place at this table?" because there were many spots.

98
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:35,000
 And I want you just to feel for a second over this trivial matter

99
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 of what it feels like to be denied a place at the table.

100
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:45,000
 Because for Joseph and Mary, they weren't just denied a place to eat.

101
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 They were denied a place in which they were to give birth to the Savior of the world.

102
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:56,000
 And how Mary and Joseph were treated by Bethlehem gives us some indication

103
00:07:56,000 --> 00:08:01,000
 that some of the kings that actually reign in our life, they're very subtle,

104
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:06,000
 and they actually disguise themselves and operate beneath our noses.

105
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:12,000
 And I think the warning here, a lighthearted warning, is that if we don't dethrone these kings,

106
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 one, we will certainly not be able to make room for what God would like to do in our hearts.

107
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:23,000
 But two, tragically, like the people of Bethlehem,

108
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:28,000
 they missed out in partaking in the greatest event in history,

109
00:08:28,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 being orchestrated by the living God because they were too daft to be aware.

110
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:39,000
 And so before we talk about the hidden kings in the hearts of the people of Bethlehem,

111
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:45,000
 I want to just lay out a very simple biblical context from Paul and Jesus

112
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:50,000
 so that we can understand that sometimes these kings is not as easy as,

113
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:54,000
 "Hey, pray about it. Just give it to God. He'll deal with it."

114
00:08:54,000 --> 00:09:00,000
 That's what we say, but how do you get there in practice? I want to just lay out a foundation.

115
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:05,000
 So at the very heart of the problem, what we're looking at here is a very human problem,

116
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:08,000
 is a human propensity to sin.

117
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:13,000
 And in our sin, we falsely believe that we are kings, that we are actually in control,

118
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:19,000
 that we have the right to judge what is right and wrong, and to a certain extent, of course we do.

119
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 And within scriptures, there are a lot of warnings that turn us,

120
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:27,000
 that encourage us to steer away from this deluded thinking.

121
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:32,000
 For example, in Romans 2, famously, Paul quotes from Isaiah,

122
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:37,000
 and he famously confronts this false reality,

123
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:42,000
 and he reminds us that all of us, all of us here, all of us listening,

124
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,000
 we are all not righteous in the sight of God

125
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:51,000
 because all of us live under the influence, power, and tyranny of sin.

126
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:57,000
 And a few chapters later, by Paul's own omission, he would say, he would admit,

127
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:04,000
 he would confess that, "I hate what I do because of the evil that is within my flesh.

128
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:10,000
 It is no longer that I do it, but the sin within me that causes me to do the most detestable things,

129
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:14,000
 and I hate that." This is Paul's own words.

130
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:16,000
 So now I want to tell you what Jesus hated.

131
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:23,000
 Now, if you read the scriptures, you'll realize how many times he confronts the religious leaders of his day,

132
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
 that is, the Pharisees and the Sadducees.

133
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:29,000
 And what he hated most was the fact that these religious leaders,

134
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:32,000
 who had a lot of power, prestige, and influence,

135
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:36,000
 they led the young believers astray because they were self-righteous,

136
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:40,000
 because they were hypocritical, they did not follow what they taught,

137
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:46,000
 and above all, they cared more about how religious and spiritual they looked to others

138
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:50,000
 than the well-being of the people that actually followed them.

139
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:52,000
 So Jesus hated this.

140
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:58,000
 And 25 years before Paul talked about the sin that caused him to do what he did not like,

141
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:04,000
 Jesus emphasized that what made us sinful, what caused us to turn away from the living God,

142
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:07,000
 is everything that flows from inside here.

143
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,000
 You'll remember in Matthew or Mark, Jesus says,

144
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 "From the core of our hearts, from our very being, comes everything that is evil,

145
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:21,000
 the intentions, the desires to murder for adultery, sexual immorality,

146
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 our thoughts of stealing, lying, slandering others,

147
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:30,000
 the desire to do wickedness, to do foolish things,

148
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:35,000
 the desire for extreme greed for wealth and material gain,

149
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:38,000
 where our lack of moral restraint comes from.

150
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 We think that we have all the freedom to do whatever we like, envy and of course arrogance."

151
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:50,000
 So it is upon this foundation of what Paul and Jesus hated

152
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 that I would like to draw out with a bit of biblical imagination

153
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 what the people of Bethlehem failed to dethrone, the kings that they failed to dethrone.

154
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:06,000
 And so I envision in preparing this message that the kings perhaps that they struggled with

155
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:12,000
 was their pride, was their tongues, and also was their fears.

156
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 The first king Bethlehem failed to dethrone was their sense of pride,

157
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:23,000
 because our pride within each of us refuses to be small before God.

158
00:12:23,000 --> 00:12:28,000
 Why should we? We can think, we know what to do, we've done it before,

159
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:32,000
 our experience tells us that we know better.

160
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:36,000
 But the danger is that our pride blinds us to see

161
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 that we actually need the same things before a living God.

162
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:43,000
 We need the same things to survive in this world.

163
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 We need food, we need shelter, we need clothing, we need affection,

164
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:52,000
 we need welcome and above all we need help.

165
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:56,000
 And so we forget as humans that because we're all the same,

166
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:02,000
 we then believe falsely that we know how to treat each other.

167
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:09,000
 And so I would imagine that it is Bethlehem's pride that led the people

168
00:13:09,000 --> 00:13:17,000
 to ultimately draw their hearts harsh, condemning, and condescending judgment on Mary and Joseph.

169
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:19,000
 You can imagine what they were thinking.

170
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:24,000
 They should have known better, no? Why would you have a baby out of wedlock?

171
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:30,000
 They're not even married yet. Why are they so silly and foolish to do such a thing?

172
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:34,000
 And church, I want to just ask you to remember, if you can,

173
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 how many times have you and I wrongfully or harshly misjudged our neighbor

174
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 and our brother and sisters when it was never in our place to

175
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:47,000
 because we didn't actually understand what they were going through inside.

176
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:53,000
 Bethlehem didn't understand what Mary was going to do for God.

177
00:13:53,000 --> 00:14:01,000
 Bethlehem's pride led them to believe that they were morally and spiritually more superior

178
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:06,000
 and they thought in their pride and arrogance that they had to hold Mary and Joseph

179
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:08,000
 accountable for their wrongdoing.

180
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:12,000
 And therefore, they thought, "Okay, this is how we're going to punish them.

181
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:15,000
 We are going to turn them away and we are not going to host them

182
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:18,000
 because once again, they should have known better."

183
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:24,000
 The second king, Bethlehem, allowed to remain enthroned in their hearts

184
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:29,000
 is the natural tendency to gossip and to slander them

185
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:32,000
 because they thought that they had the right.

186
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:38,000
 So church, imagine if this week today we hear that Mary and Joseph were going to come visit us.

187
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:42,000
 Can you imagine what kind of conversations we would have individually

188
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:44,000
 but also as a community when we gather?

189
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:47,000
 It's like, "Hey, did you hear Mary and Joseph are coming? What do you think?"

190
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:52,000
 Imagine how much gossip, how we would talk about them behind their backs.

191
00:14:52,000 --> 00:15:03,000
 And as Jesus taught us, it is within our sinful nature to actually enjoy gossip,

192
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:08,000
 to enjoy slandering and, I mean, based on all the stuff we like watching,

193
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:13,000
 we actually get some kind of kick out of seeing someone's moral downfall

194
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:19,000
 because the very need to do this comes deep within our hearts.

195
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:25,000
 The author of James, in James 3, verse 8-10, I don't think it's on PowerPoint,

196
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 but this is what he says about our tongues.

197
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:33,000
 He says, "Who can tame the tongue, a restless evil full of deadly poison?

198
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:37,000
 With the tongue we bless the Lord our Father, we sing praises to Him,

199
00:15:37,000 --> 00:15:41,000
 and with it we curse people made in the image of God.

200
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:45,000
 From the same mouth comes blessing and curse."

201
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:49,000
 My brothers and sister, James says, "This ought not to be so."

202
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:53,000
 In Luke, chapter 6, verse 45, Jesus says,

203
00:15:53,000 --> 00:15:58,000
 "Whether you're having a good day or you're having a bad and terrible day,"

204
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:04,000
 Jesus says, "out of the abundance of our hearts the mouth speaks."

205
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:09,000
 So this means that if our heart's intent right now is ill-meaning,

206
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:14,000
 it's mean-spirited, we have nothing good to say,

207
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:20,000
 then you can easily imagine how much hurt and harm and wounding our words can cause.

208
00:16:20,000 --> 00:16:24,000
 It is our inability to hold our tongue many times

209
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:32,000
 that causes the most strife and dissension and hurt within our relationships.

210
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:37,000
 And scriptures say that Mary and Joseph didn't just endure gossip and slander

211
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:39,000
 as they approached Bethlehem.

212
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:43,000
 According to the Gospel of Matthew, it says that they stayed a little longer

213
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:48,000
 in Bethlehem before they fled to Egypt.

214
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:55,000
 In preparing for today's message, I was made aware of all the little careless words

215
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:58,000
 that come out of my mouth, all the little times that I came to you

216
00:16:58,000 --> 00:17:01,000
 and wanting to know how this couple was doing.

217
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:04,000
 I was secretly really gossiping.

218
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:07,000
 I was just curious and wanting to know.

219
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:10,000
 And, you know, thinking back, I just think in the moment when we gossip,

220
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:12,000
 it feels great.

221
00:17:12,000 --> 00:17:18,000
 But oftentimes, there's instant regret because I realize every little word

222
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:22,000
 has the power to destroy, to break someone's spirit,

223
00:17:22,000 --> 00:17:27,000
 or our words can build up and encourage someone.

224
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:29,000
 And I like to think about toothpaste.

225
00:17:29,000 --> 00:17:31,000
 I learned this in marriage prep.

226
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:34,000
 I thought it's completely useful.

227
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:37,000
 Our words is like toothpaste, right?

228
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:39,000
 Once it comes out, you can't force it back in.

229
00:17:39,000 --> 00:17:41,000
 You can't unforget it.

230
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:46,000
 You can't unhear what someone said about us, and it really hurts us.

231
00:17:46,000 --> 00:17:49,000
 And so this is something that I do personally.

232
00:17:49,000 --> 00:17:55,000
 Before every conversation I have, before every big meeting, I check myself.

233
00:17:55,000 --> 00:17:57,000
 I premeditate, how is my heart doing?

234
00:17:57,000 --> 00:18:00,000
 Because if I am in a bad mood, if I'm cranky, if I'm angry,

235
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:04,000
 I want to make sure and check what I have to say, whether it's worthwhile,

236
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:09,000
 whether it's going to be encouraging, or is it just going to be worthless.

237
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:17,000
 And what really humbles me is that I'm mindful that our words have this power.

238
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:21,000
 And we as Hong Kong people know how busy we are, right?

239
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:24,000
 We say this all the time, "From here," and we tell ourselves that.

240
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:28,000
 And what also keeps my mouth just shut when I shouldn't be talking

241
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:33,000
 is I don't need more relational problems because of what I say.

242
00:18:33,000 --> 00:18:37,000
 And so that keeps me just meditating.

243
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:45,000
 So the last king, I feel like Bethlehem allowed to be enthroned in their hearts

244
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:47,000
 was their own fears.

245
00:18:47,000 --> 00:18:51,000
 It was Bethlehem's own fears that were very self-focused.

246
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:54,000
 It was self-preserving fears.

247
00:18:54,000 --> 00:19:00,000
 Could it be that the people of Bethlehem feared more for their own reputation

248
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:05,000
 than the well-being of a pregnant teenage mother?

249
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:12,000
 Was it easier to say to Mary and Joseph that there was no room in our city

250
00:19:12,000 --> 00:19:17,000
 than to deal with the social shame that would come from hosting them?

251
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:20,000
 After all, what would the neighboring towns, what would the Sadducees,

252
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:26,000
 what would the Pharisees think of us as a town if we hosted such sinners?

253
00:19:26,000 --> 00:19:31,000
 And so perhaps it was out of fear that Bethlehem,

254
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:36,000
 and out of fear of losing their social status, having their reputation tarnished,

255
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:40,000
 and having their lives interrupted, that they thought it was easier

256
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:44,000
 to close their hearts to Mary and Joseph than to welcome them.

257
00:19:44,000 --> 00:19:47,000
 The people of Bethlehem's response to Mary and Joseph

258
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:50,000
 confronts us with a very stark question.

259
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:56,000
 And it's this question, "Are we too worried about what others might think of us?

260
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:59,000
 And are we fearful of how our reputations might be tarnished

261
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:03,000
 if we really lived out what Jesus called us to live out?"

262
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:06,000
 I want to give you an example here, because I know sometimes we think,

263
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:10,000
 "Well, we're not Bethlehem. Of course we would know if God came by.

264
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:12,000
 We would open up our hearts."

265
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:14,000
 But I want to give you a good example.

266
00:20:14,000 --> 00:20:17,000
 You wake up tomorrow, you're in your classroom, you're at your workplace,

267
00:20:17,000 --> 00:20:20,000
 you're hanging out, you're having a lunch dinner with a group of friends,

268
00:20:20,000 --> 00:20:22,000
 and most of them are not believers.

269
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:26,000
 Most of them don't know anything about your faith, about Jesus, about God.

270
00:20:26,000 --> 00:20:28,000
 And so at some point in the conversation, they're like,

271
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:33,000
 "Hey, we had a debate here. Can you answer us your question?

272
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:35,000
 We have a question for you.

273
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:39,000
 Are all of us, though we're not believers, are we going to heaven with you?

274
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:44,000
 Now, I don't know where you are in your theology and what you believe

275
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:49,000
 about what happens to us after death.

276
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:53,000
 And 1 Peter, he says in chapter 3, verse 15, he says,

277
00:20:53,000 --> 00:20:56,000
 "Always be prepared to give an answer to everyone who asks you,

278
00:20:56,000 --> 00:20:59,000
 to give the reason for the hope that you have.

279
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:02,000
 Do this with gentleness and respect."

280
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:09,000
 So in that moment, will you be worried about what others think of you?

281
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:14,000
 Will it hinder you from sharing what you understand currently

282
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:20,000
 about the afterlife and about eternal life and that God has hope for us?

283
00:21:20,000 --> 00:21:24,000
 And this is just one of countless examples that held me back

284
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:28,000
 from having certain hard conversations in the last many years.

285
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:31,000
 And there were many times where I feel like I was disobedient to God

286
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:34,000
 because I was too scared of having my life interrupted,

287
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 having my schedule interrupted.

288
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:40,000
 But of course, there are many times where I just said,

289
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:44,000
 "I would overcome this fear and just brave these difficult conversations."

290
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:49,000
 And in those moments, we experienced God's grace together.

291
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:53,000
 And one of the biggest lessons I continue to learn again and again,

292
00:21:53,000 --> 00:21:58,000
 week in, week out, is how Satan uses our fears and exaggerates them,

293
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:03,000
 causes us to do nothing to love our neighbor and sister.

294
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:09,000
 And he uses our fears to intimidate us like Goliath intimidating David

295
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:14,000
 so that we would remain useless for God.

296
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:19,000
 But once again, what really humbles me and what encourages me to have these

297
00:22:19,000 --> 00:22:23,000
 and not let our fears give in is to remember who ultimately,

298
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:26,000
 who holds the power to transform our hearts,

299
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:30,000
 who allows us and gives us the courage to overcome our fears

300
00:22:30,000 --> 00:22:34,000
 so that we can do what God has asked us to do.

301
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:40,000
 So church, I want to recap that with a little bit of biblical imagination

302
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:45,000
 that the kings that Bethlehem struggled to dethrone was their pride,

303
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:50,000
 was their gossiping and slandering, and it was their fears that held them back.

304
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:55,000
 And once again, I want to remind us that the people of Bethlehem were humans

305
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:00,000
 like you and I, and so we have the same problems, we have the same struggles,

306
00:23:00,000 --> 00:23:04,000
 and therefore we cannot just ignore it, we cannot just justify it away.

307
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:09,000
 We need to, through our lifetime, figure out how do we dethrone these kings

308
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:13,000
 that constantly come and subtly manipulate us,

309
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:17,000
 cause us to lead and be led astray by God.

310
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:21,000
 Not by God, but by the enemy.

311
00:23:21,000 --> 00:23:25,000
 Ironically, it was Bethlehem's pride, it was their tongues,

312
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:29,000
 it was their gossiping, it was their hardened hearts

313
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:33,000
 that caused them to not welcome the only one

314
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:36,000
 who could actually make them righteous.

315
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:40,000
 That they missed out on the opportunity of hosting the only one

316
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:44,000
 that could truly transform their hearts, because they,

317
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:47,000
 like the Pharisees later on in Jesus' ministry,

318
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:51,000
 they would judge Mary and Joseph only by the surface.

319
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:55,000
 The Pharisees and Sadducees would judge Jesus' unusual teaching,

320
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:59,000
 his unusual, incredible miracles, and say,

321
00:23:59,000 --> 00:24:01,000
 "We want nothing to do with him."

322
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:05,000
 And by doing so, they missed out completely on the opportunity

323
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:08,000
 to host the Savior of the world.

324
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:13,000
 And so I want to propose that perhaps the problem Bethlehem had

325
00:24:13,000 --> 00:24:16,000
 was not a housing crisis once again.

326
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:17,000
 It was not just their pride.

327
00:24:17,000 --> 00:24:21,000
 It was not just their gossiping and what was inside their hearts

328
00:24:21,000 --> 00:24:26,000
 and their fears, but they were telltale sounds of something little deeper.

329
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:32,000
 And fundamentally, I think Bethlehem struggled with a welcoming problem.

330
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:36,000
 Bethlehem had an unwillingness.

331
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:40,000
 They were unwilling and an inability to show the very welcome

332
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:43,000
 that God had shown them.

333
00:24:43,000 --> 00:24:48,000
 One of my favorite passages that I often reflect on is Mark 10,

334
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:51,000
 verse 13 to 16, where Jesus says,

335
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:58,000
 "Whoever welcomes one such as a child in my name welcomes me."

336
00:24:58,000 --> 00:24:59,000
 This grounds me.

337
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:02,000
 This keeps me humble, because in Jesus' day,

338
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:06,000
 this was such a radical teaching, because children in Jesus' day,

339
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:08,000
 they were literally nobodies.

340
00:25:08,000 --> 00:25:10,000
 They were as good as slaves.

341
00:25:10,000 --> 00:25:12,000
 They did not have status at all.

342
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:16,000
 Today, our children, they flourish because they have everything.

343
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:17,000
 They have rights.

344
00:25:17,000 --> 00:25:19,000
 They have privileges.

345
00:25:19,000 --> 00:25:22,000
 They are well loved.

346
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:27,000
 And so can you imagine how radical this teaching is?

347
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:31,000
 Jesus is saying to Bethlehem, to everyone who would listen,

348
00:25:31,000 --> 00:25:34,000
 "Treat this stranger.

349
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:40,000
 Treat this person who is considered by society to be worthless,

350
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:45,000
 who has no wealth, no reputation, nothing that you would envy them for.

351
00:25:45,000 --> 00:25:48,000
 I want you to treat them like you treat me,

352
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:54,000
 because this from now on is the way in God's kingdom."

353
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:57,000
 And so for Bethlehem to not welcome Mary and Joseph,

354
00:25:57,000 --> 00:26:01,000
 even though they may not have known whether they knew or not what was going on,

355
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:04,000
 the fact that they didn't welcome them was like, in effect,

356
00:26:04,000 --> 00:26:07,000
 them turning away Yahweh.

357
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:15,000
 And so in this Advent season, Jesus says to us that if we are able to show someone

358
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:21,000
 that Hong Kong shuns with care and hospitality and grace,

359
00:26:21,000 --> 00:26:24,000
 then we don't render a service and love just to them,

360
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:28,000
 but we also render it onto Jesus himself.

361
00:26:28,000 --> 00:26:33,000
 How many times did we ourselves wish that we were welcomed

362
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:39,000
 by those we're seeking grace from in our greatest moment of need and desperation,

363
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:42,000
 grief and anguish?

364
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:47,000
 This is a silly thing, but I wonder if someone went back into the future

365
00:26:47,000 --> 00:26:51,000
 to Bethlehem 30 years prior and said, "Guys, guys, guys, guys, please listen to me.

366
00:26:51,000 --> 00:26:55,000
 You guys are about to make the silliest mistake.

367
00:26:55,000 --> 00:26:57,000
 You have to welcome Mary and Joseph."

368
00:26:57,000 --> 00:27:00,000
 I wonder whether Bethlehem would have listened.

369
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:04,000
 I wonder whether they would have humbled themselves and dethroned all the kings

370
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:14,000
 so that every house could make room and that they would fight to host Mary and Joseph.

371
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:19,000
 I often think about us as a church, right, because a lot of us,

372
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:22,000
 majority of us in this room, we are Christians.

373
00:27:22,000 --> 00:27:25,000
 But just because we're Christians doesn't necessarily mean

374
00:27:25,000 --> 00:27:28,000
 we know how to welcome someone.

375
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:32,000
 It doesn't necessarily mean that we know how to treat someone.

376
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:36,000
 And so I wonder in a very sobering way whether we are a welcoming church

377
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:39,000
 because I hear many things, and I'd rather not hear them,

378
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:45,000
 but I often do think about if Jesus came in a pregnant mother,

379
00:27:45,000 --> 00:27:52,000
 if Jesus came through a hurting child, would we be welcoming?

380
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:57,000
 And I say this with seriousness, but I also want to invite all of us today

381
00:27:57,000 --> 00:28:00,000
 to reflect on our lives and how welcoming we are.

382
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:07,000
 And I want to especially say that if you are in a position of power,

383
00:28:07,000 --> 00:28:11,000
 you have the ability to turn someone away.

384
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:15,000
 People look to you in your schools, in your workplace, in your homes,

385
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:19,000
 in your communities, they look to you for encouragement.

386
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:23,000
 I want you to reflect on today's message because you have the power

387
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:28,000
 to encourage them, to bless them, but also to turn them away

388
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:32,000
 and make them feel unwelcome.

389
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:37,000
 And I say this because, one, we are held accountable to how we welcome

390
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:41,000
 those in front of us as Christ welcomed us on the cross.

391
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:44,000
 But also I think the stakes are too high.

392
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:48,000
 Nowadays we cannot afford for someone to turn away from God

393
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:54,000
 because we are too much like Bethlehem in the moment.

394
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:57,000
 Perhaps in a way of closing our time together today,

395
00:28:57,000 --> 00:29:02,000
 I want to share a memory that surfaced for me as I was preparing this message.

396
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:08,000
 I want to tell you a time that really radically changed me when I was 17,

397
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:10,000
 a year after I became a Christian.

398
00:29:10,000 --> 00:29:12,000
 I grew up in Canada, I grew up in Toronto.

399
00:29:12,000 --> 00:29:15,000
 I lived a privileged life in middle class.

400
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:19,000
 There wasn't much poverty. I had everything I needed as a child.

401
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:21,000
 My parents were amazing to me.

402
00:29:21,000 --> 00:29:25,000
 Schooling was great, great friends, nothing to really complain about.

403
00:29:25,000 --> 00:29:27,000
 So that was my background.

404
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:29,000
 And so one time, I want to tell you about my friend Walter,

405
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:32,000
 who is still a very dear friend to me. He's still in Canada.

406
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:35,000
 And so when we're 17, we went to different schools.

407
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:40,000
 He said, "Hey, this weekday after school, you want to come downtown with me?"

408
00:29:40,000 --> 00:29:44,000
 where there was poverty, where it's very exciting for a teenager to hang out.

409
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:47,000
 All the coolest shops. Everything happened downtown.

410
00:29:47,000 --> 00:29:50,000
 And so of course, I would take up his offer.

411
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:54,000
 And so I said, "Yes, Walter, I'd love to come down to downtown with you,

412
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:56,000
 have dinner with your friend."

413
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:00,000
 And so we traveled down together, went downtown, came up the subway,

414
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:02,000
 and we walked towards the restaurant.

415
00:30:02,000 --> 00:30:05,000
 And I remember asking him, "Hey, is your friend meeting us there,

416
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:07,000
 or are we going to pick him up or her up?"

417
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:10,000
 And he said, "Oh, don't worry, they'll show up."

418
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:12,000
 So anyways, we walked to our restaurant.

419
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:15,000
 And then suddenly, my friend Walter just stopped

420
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:19,000
 and spoke with what seems to be a homeless man,

421
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:21,000
 who I've not seen that much, right?

422
00:30:21,000 --> 00:30:24,000
 And so Walter started talking as though they were--

423
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:27,000
 they haven't caught up in a long time, and they were just chatting,

424
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:29,000
 and I was invited in the conversation.

425
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:34,000
 And at some point, the man got up, and we went to the restaurant together.

426
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:38,000
 And in that moment, I realized Walter wanted me to join him

427
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:41,000
 to have dinner with this homeless gentleman.

428
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:46,000
 And so time went by, had a lovely conversation, we had Taco Bell,

429
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:50,000
 not great food, but back then it was great.

430
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:51,000
 Amazing conversation.

431
00:30:51,000 --> 00:30:55,000
 And as a way of wrapping up, Walter's like, "Oh, we need to go home.

432
00:30:55,000 --> 00:30:57,000
 Is there anything else you need from us?

433
00:30:57,000 --> 00:30:59,000
 Can we do anything for you?"

434
00:30:59,000 --> 00:31:03,000
 And the man thought about it and said, "Actually, Walter, I need new trousers."

435
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:05,000
 So guess what we did?

436
00:31:05,000 --> 00:31:07,000
 We went shopping for new trousers.

437
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:10,000
 And so then we parted ways, and I only remember two more things.

438
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:16,000
 One thing I remember, that day Walter's face was beaming from the inside out.

439
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:19,000
 And two, I remember asking him, "Walter, why do you do this?

440
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:20,000
 How often do you do this?"

441
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:23,000
 And Walter, he's just the most subtle guy.

442
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:26,000
 Even to this day, he wants no attention.

443
00:31:26,000 --> 00:31:29,000
 And I remember him just telling me that this was his way of

444
00:31:29,000 --> 00:31:33,000
 tending to the needs of this world as he can.

445
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:37,000
 And for me as a new Christian, I didn't read that much Bible at all at that time.

446
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:40,000
 I was only following what people modeled.

447
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:47,000
 And so looking back on that day fondly, I realize and I can say before you that

448
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:52,000
 to love our neighbor, to welcome the stranger, the person that you do not know,

449
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:57,000
 the person that society shuns, is two sides of the same coin.

450
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:03,000
 Walter's casual yet intentional welcome, his gracious hospitality to a man he did

451
00:32:03,000 --> 00:32:08,000
 not know at all, was used by God to provide for this man's daily needs,

452
00:32:08,000 --> 00:32:11,000
 but also for a moment of refuge and companionship.

453
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:19,000
 And this was exactly the kind of hospitality and grace that was denied Mary and Joseph.

454
00:32:19,000 --> 00:32:24,000
 In 1 Timothy 4.12, this was the first scripture that was ever given to me as a Christian.

455
00:32:24,000 --> 00:32:32,000
 1 Timothy 4.12 says, "Let no one despise you for your youthfulness,

456
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:38,000
 but set an example in speech and conduct, in love, faith, and purity."

457
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:44,000
 The thoughtfulness, the kindness, the generosity shown by a 17-year-old teenager

458
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:50,000
 whereby he extended himself over a meal to a stranger in love and in generosity

459
00:32:50,000 --> 00:32:59,000
 is exactly the kind of welcome that Jesus calls all of us to learn to exemplify.

460
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:07,000
 When I think about Walter, I then think about what is actually needed to truly welcome someone,

461
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:09,000
 which is actually not much.

462
00:33:09,000 --> 00:33:16,000
 And I can confidently say that this is something that all of us can do within our own capacity.

463
00:33:16,000 --> 00:33:22,000
 As we grow in grace, as we grow within God's grace, as we continue to listen to God's word,

464
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:26,000
 as we continue to meet in our different communities and pray together and learn

465
00:33:26,000 --> 00:33:33,000
 what it means to walk the Christian life, all of us have to reconcile with this idea

466
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:37,000
 that all of us have to welcome someone wherever you are placed.

467
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:40,000
 And this is a joy. This is a privilege.

468
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:43,000
 And I know--and I want to end with this thought.

469
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:46,000
 I know all of us are thinking about Christmas time's coming.

470
00:33:46,000 --> 00:33:49,000
 What is the gift that we can give?

471
00:33:49,000 --> 00:33:54,000
 I don't want to sound too cheesy, but I absolutely believe this.

472
00:33:54,000 --> 00:34:00,000
 One of the most needed gifts in this world right now that you can give at any time

473
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:04,000
 is the gift of welcome that overflows from a gracious heart.

474
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:09,000
 And I cannot think of any other gift, any other thing that you give to someone

475
00:34:09,000 --> 00:34:16,000
 that has so much potential to transform and to heal someone.

476
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:25,000
 So, church, can I ask us to stand, and I want to pray for us.

477
00:34:25,000 --> 00:34:34,000
 I don't know if this was a bit too heavy, but in this season of Advent,

478
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:41,000
 I want to first say that today's message is by no ways a message of condemnation,

479
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:46,000
 because all of us, in our best days and our worst days, we are like Bethlehem.

480
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:51,000
 On our best days and worst days, we have fears, we gossip,

481
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:55,000
 we say things that we don't mean and wish we could take back,

482
00:34:55,000 --> 00:34:58,000
 and we judge prematurely, harshly.

483
00:34:58,000 --> 00:35:03,000
 We do all of that, and we are in a safe place.

484
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:07,000
 And so I want to pray for us as we stand together with this heart

485
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:10,000
 that we are not condemned.

486
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:14,000
 But today's message is one of self-reflection.

487
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:18,000
 It's a call of warning.

488
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:24,000
 It's a call to acknowledge that, yes, Lord, we are all under the influence of sin,

489
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:30,000
 and yes, we do selfish things because it is within the core of our hearts.

490
00:35:30,000 --> 00:35:37,000
 And so, Father, as a church, we want to surrender to you our sinful intentions.

491
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:44,000
 Father, our hurtful words that condemn and that don't bring peace or edification.

492
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:47,000
 Father, the way we gossip, the way we enjoy it,

493
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:52,000
 Father, and the fears that cause us to do nothing for our brothers and sisters,

494
00:35:52,000 --> 00:35:55,000
 Father, we repent of these ways.

495
00:35:55,000 --> 00:36:00,000
 And, Father, we just ask that you would teach us for the rest of our days

496
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:05,000
 to welcome our neighbor, our brother, our sister, our stranger,

497
00:36:05,000 --> 00:36:07,000
 even our enemy as you welcome us.

498
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:11,000
 And this is the highest calling, Jesus.

499
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:21,000
 This is the call and the privilege and opportunity that you invite us to join you in.

500
00:36:21,000 --> 00:36:24,000
 And so, Father, help us in the days ahead to build up,

501
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:29,000
 to encourage the comfort with our lives, with our welcome, with our words,

502
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:33,000
 with the resources you've given us.

503
00:36:33,000 --> 00:36:37,000
 So, Holy Spirit, would you give us courage to see what you're saying

504
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:39,000
 and how you're leading us, Jesus.

505
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:42,000
 In your name we pray, amen.

